    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-01-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-01-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="193"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d193">
                <head>193. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d193fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives and Records Administration, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1964-66, <gloss
                            target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 18 GIB. Confidential. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_OFVJ1">Ortiz</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1966-01-28">January 28,
                            1966</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Gibraltar</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">Spain</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>The <persName corresp="#p_MVAMA1">Marques de Merry del
                                    Val</persName>, Spanish Ambassador</item>
                            <item>Nuno Aguirre de Carcer, Minister-Counselor, Embassy of
                                Spain</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">U.S.</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>Assistant Secretary <persName corresp="#p_LJM1">Leddy</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_OFVJ1">Frank V. Ortiz</persName>, <gloss
                                    target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>:<gloss target="#t_WE1">WE</gloss>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The Ambassador called to inquire about the <persName corresp="#p_SM2"
                        >Stewart</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> conversations
                    and to discuss Spain’s position on the Gibraltar dispute.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d193fn2">A copy of the memorandum of <persName corresp="#p_RD1"
                            >Rusk</persName>’s January 27 conversation with <persName
                            corresp="#p_SM2">Stewart</persName> regarding Gibraltar is ibid.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LJM1">Leddy</persName> said the Gibraltar dispute had
                    been mentioned briefly during Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SM2"
                    >Stewart</persName>’s visit. However the United States had made clear <pb
                        facs="0427" n="391" xml:id="pg_391"/> its desire not to become involved in
                    this dispute. The Ambassador said he hoped the United States would comprehend
                    Spain’s point of view which, he said, was not one of hostility to the defense
                    efforts of the West since Spain’s contributions to that effort were well
                    known.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LJM1">Leddy</persName> said Spain’s view of the matter
                    was receiving very careful consideration by the Department. We would soon be in
                    a position to reply. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LJM1">Leddy</persName> asked what
                    purpose Spain had in mind in raising the Gibraltar problem in this form.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador replied that Spain’s purpose was to put the Gibraltar dispute in
                    its proper context, namely as a bilateral dispute between Spain and the <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>. Spain wished it to be clear that Gibraltar could
                    not be considered by Spain as a <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> base.</p>
            </div>
